    "abstract": [
        {
            "text": "Words: 493 (Limit: 750) | Refences: 8 (Limit 8) | Figure: 1 Dear Editor: We read the article of D'Amico et al., 1 discussing the pathogenesis, epidemiology, prevention, and management of diarrhea among patients with Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19), caused by the Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2). We agree on the importance of such reviews, primarily targeted to gastroenterologists. Nevertheless, we would like to discuss additional implications and analyses presented by D'Amico et al., 1 regarding the prevalence of diarrhea derived from available published studies, and its comparison with SARS-CoV and the Middle East Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus (MERS-CoV) infections.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Abstract"
        },
        {
            "text": "Authors analyzed in their table 1 results from 20 studies, with a pooled prevalence of 10.4%, although no information on the meta-analysis model was provided. We used that data, and additionally included 11 novel studies, published till May 3, 2020, also assessing the frequency of diarrhea among COVID-19 patients. Now with 3,335 patients from 31 studies, we approached with random-and fixed-effects models to determine that pooled prevalence. We used the Open Meta-Analyst software. For the first, we found that 13.8% of patients presented diarrhea (95%CI 10.6-17.0%), and for the fixed-effects model, 6.1% (95%CI 5.4-6.9%) (Figure 1 ). In the case of SARS-CoV and MERS-CoV, D'Amico et al., 1 did not provide pooled prevalences for comparisons with SARS-CoV-2. Then, we used the data they presented about these previous coronaviruses regarding diarrhea, and we added two studies on SARS-CoV. Combining data from 735 patients with SARS-CoV, the pooled prevalence yields 12.4% (95CI 4.8-",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 626,
                    "end": 635,
                    "text": "(Figure 1",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "section": "Abstract"
        }
    ],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Rhuvi Villamizar-Pe\u00f1a, 1,a Estefan\u00eda Guti\u00e9rrez-Ocampo, 1 20.0%) in the random-effects model, and 2.3% (95%CI 1.3-3.3%) in the fixed-effects model ( Figure 1 ). In the case of MERS-CoV, this was 23.1% (95%CI 10.7-35.4%) and",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 55,
                    "end": 56,
                    "text": "1",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF0"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 148,
                    "end": 156,
                    "text": "Figure 1",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "section": "Pooled Prevalence of Diarrhea among COVID-19 Patients"
        },
        {
            "text": "17.5% (95%CI 13.1-21.9%), respectively ( Figure 1 ).",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 41,
                    "end": 49,
                    "text": "Figure 1",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "section": "Pooled Prevalence of Diarrhea among COVID-19 Patients"
        },
        {
            "text": "In addition to the cohort, cross-sectional, and case series studies, D'Amico et al., 1 also involved three case reports. We also looked at that and found six more case reports.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Pooled Prevalence of Diarrhea among COVID-19 Patients"
        },
        {
            "text": "Most of them are from China (5), followed by Japan (2), USA (1), and Lebanon (1), with a median diarrhea duration of 3 days, and regarding the number of evacuations, those ranging from 2 to 6 per day. [2] [3] [4] [5] [6] [7] In a previous meta-analysis, we found that diarrhea was reported among 6.1% (95%CI 2.4-9.7%) patients with COVID-19 (6 studies, 457 patients), 8 which is the same prevalence obtained now with 31 studies and 3,335 patients by the fixed-effects model in the current analysis ( Figure 1 ). Although this would be considered a low prevalence, the COVID-19 pandemic has affected 3.8 million people worldwide (May 8, 2020), translating into between 210,051 and 268,399 diarrhea associated cases (based on 95% CI for pooled prevalence).",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 201,
                    "end": 204,
                    "text": "[2]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 205,
                    "end": 208,
                    "text": "[3]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF3"
                },
                {
                    "start": 209,
                    "end": 212,
                    "text": "[4]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF4"
                },
                {
                    "start": 213,
                    "end": 216,
                    "text": "[5]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                },
                {
                    "start": 217,
                    "end": 220,
                    "text": "[6]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF6"
                },
                {
                    "start": 221,
                    "end": 224,
                    "text": "[7]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF7"
                },
                {
                    "start": 368,
                    "end": 369,
                    "text": "8",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF9"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 500,
                    "end": 508,
                    "text": "Figure 1",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "section": "Pooled Prevalence of Diarrhea among COVID-19 Patients"
        },
        {
            "text": "Because the SARS-CoV-2 may directly or indirectly affect the enteric mucosa, 1 diarrhea and other gastrointestinal findings should raise clinical suspicion for COVID-19, with or without presence of fever, cough and other respiratory and non-respiratory manifestations. 8 Finally, as D'Amico et al., 1 mentioned, fecal-oral spread transmission may be an additional source of transmission that deserves more research and subsequent preventive interventions.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 269,
                    "end": 270,
                    "text": "8",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF9"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Pooled Prevalence of Diarrhea among COVID-19 Patients"
        },
        {
